answers.body_markdown:
Just use the [constructor][1] of `LinkedList` that accepts an `IEnumerable` parameter:

    LinkedList&lt;Point&gt; node =
        new LinkedList&lt;Point&gt;(LinkedPoints.Where(x =&gt; x.X + x.Y / someValue % 2 == 0));

----------

You can also create an extension method similar to the `.ToList()` and `.ToArray()` methods:

    static class EnumerableExtensions
    {
        public static LinkedList&lt;T&gt; ToLinkedList&lt;T&gt;(this IEnumerable&lt;T&gt; collection)
        {
            return new LinkedList&lt;T&gt;(collection);
        }
    }

**Usage:**

    LinkedList&lt;Point&gt; node = 
        LinkedPoints.Where(x =&gt; x.X + x.Y / someValue % 2 == 0).ToLinkedList();

----------

Notes:
-----

- `.Where&lt;Point&gt;` can be simplified to just `.Where` because the type is inferred from the list.
- As [mjwills][2] indicated in the comments, it&#39;s highly recommended to use parenthesis in your condition to make the calculation logic clearer and to avoid mistakes. See [Arithmetic operators precedence and associativity][3] for reference. Also, beware not to fall victim for unintended [Integer Division][4].


  [1]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.collections.generic.linkedlist-1.-ctor?view=netframework-4.8#System_Collections_Generic_LinkedList_1__ctor_System_Collections_Generic_IEnumerable__0__
  [2]: https://stackoverflow.com/users/34092/mjwills
  [3]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/operators/arithmetic-operators#operator-precedence-and-associativity
